pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
Overview

SharePoint Syntex lets you create models to identify, classify, and extract the information you need. Models have value in helping to resolve business issues for search, business processes, compliance, and many others.

You can choose from three types of models:

  • Document understanding model
  • Form processing model
  • Prebuilt model

Models are generally used for the same purpose, but key differences will affect which one you choose to use. (If you're using the content center provided with this preview, you won't be able to create a form processing model or a prebuilt model.)

pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
Document understanding models
​​​​​​​

Document understanding models use AI to automatically classify documents within a SharePoint document library and, if you choose, to extract specific information from these documents. Document understanding models are created in a content center and classify and extract information from unstructured documents.

Unstructured documents might include statements of work, contracts, business letters, legal documents, product testing reports, project documents, or any text-based content that isn't structured like a form.

pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
Form processing models
​​​​​​​

Form processing models focus on identifying and extracting information from structured and semi-structured documents. Form processing models use machine learning technology from Microsoft Power Apps AI Builder (uses AI Builder credits). AI capabilities identify and extract necessary information, helping automate business processes.

Structured or semi-structured documents might include purchase orders, invoices, billing statements, expense forms, work orders, or tax forms, all of which have specific structures that look more like a form.

pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
Prebuilt models
​​​​​​​

Prebuilt models are a new addition to SharePoint Syntex. These models are pre-trained to recognize documents and the components in documents. They also work on image files and PDF files. You can immediately apply prebuilt models to libraries as they are. They don't need additional training or labeling, and no training file is needed.

You can customize a prebuilt model, review it to see how it works on your documents, and customize the names to match your documents or naming convention. You can also turn off suggested components that aren't applicable.

STEP 1
Start with a content center

A content center is a special SharePoint site that enables you to create, train, and manage models. You can also view and track which models are applied to which document libraries.

You can either use a default content center or create a new content center, or you can use the content center provided with this preview. If you use the provided content center, you can create and test models but won't be able to apply the models to a document library.

STEP 2
Create and train a classifier

A classifier is a type of document understanding model that identifies the document type and then classifies it accordingly. You'll add an explanation as part of your classifier model to describe what will be either classified or extracted.

To jump-start your understanding of how to create your own models, you can import a sample model. The sample model lets you examine model components, such as its classifier, extractors, and explanations. You can also use the sample files to train the model.

STEP 3
Create and train an extractor

An extractor is a part of a document understanding model that pulls the information from your documents. You can create an extractor before or after you've created your document understanding model. You'll create an extractor for each part in a document that you want to extract.

As part of your extractor, you can add an explanation that describes what information will be extracted.

pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
SharePoint Syntex uses AI and machine learning to organize your content. It's a content understanding, processing, and compliance service that automatically and thoughtfully organizes and classifies documents and forms in your SharePoint library – transforming your content into knowledge.

AI and machine learning help you better understand your content by accurately and efficiently classifying and extracting relevant information. Rather than clicking and sorting through hundreds or even thousands of files, SharePoint Syntex extracts data for you, streamlining the search and discovery process. This returns valuable time to you and your team. You can not only dive deeper into your content to truly understand it, now you can also increase document insight and control.

View this video to learn more about SharePoint Syntex.​​​​​​​

pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
Overview
​​​​​​​

Maintaining compliance and data governance is critical today. Your customers and clients need to trust that the data and information your business captures is used in a secure and thoughtful way. Having a full, clear view into your content landscape is essential to achieve this. Knowing exactly where information is taken from and how it is categorized sets up your organization for compliance success. SharePoint Syntex helps you reduce risks and ensure your information is safe.

pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
Retention labels
​​​​​​​

Retention labels give you the option to apply retention settings to your documents. Retention settings are policies defining how documents are kept or deleted. Retention labels enforce who can delete documents and when they can delete them.

For retention labels to be available to apply to your document understanding and form processing models, they need to be created and published in the Microsoft 365 Compliance Center.

pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
Sensitivity labels
​​​​​​​

Sensitivity labels let you apply encryption, sharing, and conditional access policies to the documents that your models identify. SharePoint Syntex models honor the label order rules and do not overwrite an existing label that was manually applied by a user to the file.

For sensitivity labels to be available to apply to your document understanding models, they need to be created and published in the Microsoft 365 Compliance Center.

Sensitivity labels currently aren't available for form processing models.
